content.beginner:
You annotate variables with `: type`:

```typescript
let name: string = 'Alice';
let age: number = 30;
let isAdmin: boolean = true;
let scores: number[] = [95, 87, 92];
```

TypeScript can also **infer** types â€” you don't always need to write them!

Use `interface` to describe the shape of an object:

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email?: string; // optional
}

function greet(user: User) {
  console.log('Hello, ' + user.name);
}
```

A union type means 'this OR that':

```typescript
type Status = 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';

function getColor(status: Status): string {
  if (status === 'loading') return 'gray';
  if (status === 'success') return 'green';
  return 'red';
}
```

Generics let you write reusable code that works with different types:

```typescript
function identity<T>(value: T): T {
  return value;
}

identity<string>('hello'); // T = string
identity<number>(42);      // T = number
```

Think of `T` as a type variable â€” a placeholder for the actual type.

TypeScript narrows types inside conditionals:

```typescript
function printLength(val: string | number) {
  if (typeof val === 'string') {
    console.log(val.length); // TS knows it's a string here
  } else {
    console.log(val.toFixed(2)); // TS knows it's a number
  }
}
```

TypeScript has built-in utility types to transform types:

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

type PartialUser = Partial<User>;   // all optional
type ReadonlyUser = Readonly<User>; // all readonly
type UserPreview = Pick<User, 'id' | 'name'>; // only those fields
```

content.intermediate:
Prefer `const` objects over enums for most cases:
```typescript
const Direction = { Up: 'UP', Down: 'DOWN' } as const;
type Direction = typeof Direction[keyof typeof Direction];
```
This is tree-shakeable, works at runtime like a plain object, and avoids enum's non-standard JS output.

content.beginner:
Type your function parameters and return value:

```typescript
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

const greet = (name: string): string => {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
};
```

TypeScript will catch if you pass the wrong type!
